Sir '''Godfrey Russell Vick''' [[King's Counsel|KC]] (24 December 1892 – 27 September 1958)<ref name="www">''Who Was Who 1897-2006'' (2007)</ref> was an [[England|English]] [[lawyer]], [[judge]] and [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal Party]] politician.

==Background==
Vick was born [[West Hartlepool]], the son of Richard William Vick [[Justice of the Peace|JP]] and Emily ''née'' Oughtred. He was educated at [[The Leys School]] and [[Jesus College, Cambridge]]. He married Marjorie Hester Compston and the couple had two daughters and two sons, the younger of whom, [[Arnold Russell]], also became a barrister and judge.<ref name="www"/> 

==Professional career==
He served in the [[Durham Light Infantry]] during [[World War I]], being [[called to the bar]] at the [[Inner Temple]] in 1917,<ref name="www"/> and practised successfully, largely as a [[criminal law]]yer.<ref name="wb">Wade Baron (1966) ''p.''58</ref> He served both as Chairman of the Bar Council and variously as a [[recorder (judge)|recorder]] in [[Richmond, Yorkshire|Richmond]] (1930-1931), [[Halifax, West Yorkshire|Halifax]] (1931-1939) and [[Newcastle-upon-Tyne]] (1939-1956). He was subsequently made a [[county court]] judge, and became a [[bencher]] of the Inner Temple.<ref name="www"/>

His service on [[public enquiry|public enquiries]] included:
*[[London County Council]] [[Detention of suspects|remand]] homes (1944);<ref name="wb"/>
*The [[black market]] in [[petrol]] (1948);<ref name="wb"/>
*[[Lynskey tribunal]] into [[political corruption]] (1948);<ref name="wb"/>
*Ill-treatment of prisoners at [[Liverpool (HM Prison)|HM Prison Liverpool]] (1958).<ref>Home Office (1958)</ref>

==Political career==
He contested the constituency of [[Bishop Auckland (UK Parliament constituency)|Bishop Auckland]] at the [[United Kingdom general election, 1918|1918 General Election]] for the [[Liberal Party (UK)|Coalition Liberals]] and finished second. 

In 1919 he contested the constituency of [[Shoreditch (UK Parliament constituency)|Shoreditch]] in the [[London County Council election, 1919]]. He ran for the Liberal backed [[Progressive Party (London)|Progressive Party]] and narrowly missed out on election.

He contested the constituency of [[The Hartlepools (UK Parliament constituency)|The Hartlepools]] at the [[United Kingdom general election, 1945|1945 General Election]] for the [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal Party]] and finished third.

